Aya Hijazi. (Mohamed el-Raai, AP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Washington - An Egyptian-American charity worker freed after nearly three years of detention in Egypt is meeting President Donald Trump at the White House.Sean Spicer, the White House press secretary, says that Trump was directly involved in negotiations to free Aya Hijazi. Hijazi and her husband, Mohamed Hassanein, an Egyptian, returned to the Washington area this week.Earlier this week, a court acquitted Hijazi of charges of child abuse. The charges were widely dismissed as bogus by human rights groups and US officials. She and her husband had established a foundation to aid street children in 2013, but were arrested along with several others in 2014.Her case was on the agenda when Trump met Egyptian President Abdel-Fattah al-Sisi earlier this month. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.